==== Grammar\
== Nominals\
Nouns have an inherent gender (masculine or feminine), with which adjectives agree. Both also decline for number (singular/plural) and case (direct/dative). Numerals function like adjectives. Fractions, when combined with a partitive, agree in gender with the partitive - e.g., in the mock sentence \'93one third of gold\'94, if \'93gold\'94 is masculine, \'93one\'94 and \'93third\'94 take masculine forms. Adjectives practically always follow the nominal they accompany. Articles don\'92t exist and definiteness is contextual.\
\
The paradigm system may seem complicated at first, but is actually relatively straightforward. There are two main categories, thematic and iotic. Both are divided into a paradigm per gender, which is subdivided into the default paradigm (\uc0\u948 ) and its alpha equivalent (\u945 ). Any noun inherently belongs to a very specific paradigm while adjectives logically fluctuate in gender - however, thematic/iotic and default/alpha is fixed per word. Below, you may find the declension table for the relevant paradigms:\
\
MASCULINE THEMATIC \uc0\u948 \
direct: -u (sg), -us (pl)\
dative: -oy (sg), -uc (pl)\
\
FEMININE THEMATIC (\uc0\u948  & \u945 )\
direct: -a (sg), -os (pl)\
dative: -ay (sg), -ap (pl)\
\
MASCULINE THEMATIC \uc0\u945 \
direct: -a (sg), -os (pl)\
dative: -oy (sg), -ap (pl)\
\
MASCULINE IOTIC (\uc0\u948  & \u945 ) and FEMININE IOTIC\
direct: -i (sg), -es (pl)\
dative: -ey (sg), -ic (pl)\
\
FEMININE IOTIC \uc0\u945 \
direct: -a (sg), -os (pl)\
dative: -ey (sg), -ic (pl)\
