== Verbs\
Verbs are without a doubt the most complicated aspect here, owing to their large conjugational tables. Like nominals, verbs are divided into two main classes, being thematic and athematic, where athematic is split further into vocalic and resonant. These three paradigms are further divided into default (\uc0\u948 ) and alpha (\u945 ). The TAM system is reasonably complicated: an indicative mood, divided into active and passive voices reflecting present, preterite and future (all also conjugating person and number) as well as a subjunctive mood, featuring the same active/passive split but simplifying tenses into non-past and past. Imperatives also exist, while infinitives are lacking. As the above text does not use subjunctives nor imperatives, these will be left out. Four participles exist, reflecting both present/past and active/passive. While a massive table would be enjoyable, only the forms used by the text are included for everyone\'92s convenience (except for the participles, which are all included and behave like adjectives). Dictionary forms reflect the indicative active 1sg present. If a secondary stem exists, it is used for the passive.\
